---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import globalCss from '../../styles/global.css?raw';

// The paste is sliced out of the site's own global.css — one source of truth.
const START = '@custom-variant dark';
const END = '/* ============== end of the Getting Started paste ==============';
const startIndex = globalCss.indexOf(START);
const endIndex = globalCss.indexOf(END);
if (startIndex === -1 || endIndex === -1)
  throw new Error('getting-started: token paste markers not found in global.css');
const tokensPaste = `@import "tailwindcss";\n\n${globalCss.slice(startIndex, endIndex).trimEnd()}\n`;

const darkToggleSnippet = `<button onclick="
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark');
  localStorage.theme = document.documentElement.classList.contains('dark') ? 'dark' : 'light';
">Toggle theme</button>`;
---

<DocsLayout title="Getting started — unscripted/ui">
  <article>
    <header class="mb-2">
      <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight">Getting started</h1>
      <p class="mt-1.5 max-w-[60ch] text-muted-foreground">
        There is nothing to install, no package, no provider, no registry command. The
        components are markup — this page is the entire setup.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="docs-prose">
      <h2>1. Have Tailwind CSS v4</h2>
      <p>
        Components are styled with Tailwind utility classes, including the newer variants
        (<code>starting:</code>, <code>transition-discrete</code>, <code>details-content:</code>).
        Any Tailwind v4.1+ setup works — Vite plugin, PostCSS, or the CLI.
      </p>

      <h2>2. Paste the tokens</h2>
      <p>
        This is the shadcn variable contract mapped to Tailwind v4's <code>@theme</code>. If your
        project already uses shadcn/ui, you already have these variables — skip the
        <code>:root</code>/<code>.dark</code> blocks and keep your theme; the components will
        match it automatically. The paste also carries two site-wide behaviors the components
        rely on: <code>interpolate-size: allow-keywords</code> (animated <code>height: auto</code>)
        and the <code>prefers-reduced-motion</code> rule.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock code={tokensPaste} lang="css" />

      <h2>3. Dark mode (optional)</h2>
      <p>
        The paste defines a <code>dark</code> variant driven by a <code>.dark</code> class on
        <code>&lt;html&gt;</code>. How that class gets there is your call — this is the one
        place where a few bytes of JavaScript are reasonable:
      </p>
      <CodeBlock code={darkToggleSnippet} lang="html" />
      <p>
        Prefer zero JS even here? Swap the variant for
        <code>@custom-variant dark (&#123;@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)&#125;)</code>-style media
        query handling and skip the toggle.
      </p>

      <h2>4. Copy components</h2>
      <p>
        Every component page has a Preview/Code switcher (itself built with this library's
        radio-tabs technique). Copy the HTML, paste it, done. Exactly one component
        (<a href="/components/carousel">Carousel</a>) ships an extra CSS block, and its page
        explains why.
      </p>

      <h2>Browser support philosophy</h2>
      <p>
        Some components use features that are Baseline and boring (dialog, details, popover).
        Others use features that shipped in Chromium first (anchor positioning, customizable
        select, CSS carousels). The rule for everything here: <strong>the fallback must be
        functional</strong>. A select without <code>base-select</code> is the classic native
        select. A dropdown without anchor positioning opens centered. A carousel without
        scroll markers still scrolls. Each component page has a support table with the exact
        versions and the exact fallback behavior.
      </p>
      <p>
        The colored badges you see on component pages are <strong>live</strong> — they're
        rendered by <code>@supports</code> blocks, so they report on the browser you're using
        right now. No user-agent sniffing, no JS. One honest limitation: <code>@supports</code>
        can only test CSS, so HTML features like <code>commandfor</code> get a table row but no
        live badge.
      </p>

      <h2>Accessibility notes</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Native elements ship their own semantics and keyboard behavior: dialog traps focus,
          details/summary announce as disclosures, radios give you arrow-key navigation.
          That's behavior JS libraries reimplement — here it's the browser's job.
        </li>
        <li>
          Where a pattern bends semantics, the component page says so out loud — see
          <a href="/components/tabs">Tabs</a>, which announces as a radio group and explains
          why that's the honest trade.
        </li>
        <li>
          Reduced motion is handled once, globally, in the token paste — every transition and
          animation in the library collapses to instant for users who ask for that.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</DocsLayout>
